issue.body:
The digest of the requirements.txt file seems to be added to the lock file, which triggers merge conflicts.

```
    "@@rules_python+//python/extensions:pip.bzl%pip": {
      "general": {
        "bzlTransitiveDigest": "Iwo5aX1NCLf2xFr7Cq4NNxpYMRA7qIh3/uaa/Kk4myg=",
        "usagesDigest": "A5I0AW9kWKM1sMWDOt7FRtMoXFL0LONjpXqb43RHBrw=",
        "recordedFileInputs": {
          "@@grpc+//requirements.bazel.txt": "95a27c3f9a46b8114d464c70ba93cda18cfe8c02004db81028f9306b2691701e",
          "@@//requirements.txt": "29c6501451ce48549f1dac1b73e0cd42ee924a3b7649ed0080254de4bbcebb7f"
        },
```

Related thread on Slack https://bazelbuild.slack.com/archives/C014RARENH0/p1731817466761249

Is this necessary?

body:
There's another potential application for this: `use_repo_rule` could use it to persist the "recommended attributes" that a repo rule implementation can return (e.g. for `sha256`). This would allow repo rules to persist and reuse hashes and other information that is costly to compute without a need for users to specify them manually in `MODULE.bazel`.

@malt3, @sluongng and I are thinking about how to make repo rules work better with BwoB. A "remote-friendly" variant of `http_archive` could rely on this capability to persist the names of files in an archive, which could then be fetched and extracted in a build rule while still allowing analysis time access to the archive contents. 

@Wyverald @meteorcloudy What do you think about that? This could resolve most of the "repo rules should be able to depend on build rules" use cases with much lower implementation complexity. https://github.com/fmeum/rbe_repos.bzl/tree/main/examples is a prototype I built to demonstrate what this could do, but it currently requires a module extension wrapper to persist information in the lockfile.
